{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"64db2aeb-1504-45d4-84c5-dd4b45ed2806","content":"I've reviewed all the project files. Here are the **3 evaluation performance anti-patterns** in this project:\n\n---\n\n### 1. 🔴 Expensive Glob — `**\\*.*` (line 9)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\nThis recursive wildcard walks the **entire directory tree** during evaluation. If large directories exist (e.g., `node_modules`, `.git`, artifacts), this becomes very slow. **Fix:** narrow the glob to specific extensions/directories, or add large dirs to `DefaultItemExcludes`.\n\n### 2. 🔴 File I/O Property Function (line 13)\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\n`System.IO.File::ReadAllText` performs **disk I/O during evaluation**, blocking the evaluation pipeline. Property functions run synchronously in the evaluation pass. **Fix:** move this to a target with `Inputs/Outputs` so it only runs during execution, not evaluation.\n\n### 3. 🟡 Deep Import Chain (3 levels)\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nEach import adds evaluation overhead. At 3 levels this is moderate, but it's a pattern that easily grows. Keep import depth shallow and consolidate where possible.\n\n---\n\n**Impact ranking:** The glob (#1) and file I/O (#2) are the most impactful — they perform real I/O during every evaluation. The import chain (#3) is a maintainability concern that compounds as the project grows.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c1bd55c4-0bad-44bf-8a78-785eb35a6d42","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I have a complete picture of the project. Let me analyze the evaluation performance issues:\n\n1. **Deep import chain**: `EvalHeavy.csproj` → `level1.props` → `level2.props` → `level3.props` — 3 levels deep. Not terrible but a pattern that can grow.\n\n2. **Expensive glob**: `<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />` — This recursive glob walks the entire directory tree during evaluation. If the directory has large subtrees (node_modules, .git, etc.), this is very expensive.\n\n\n3. **File I/O during evaluation**: Reading file contents with property functions blocks evaluation while hitting disk, which is another bottleneck. The 3-level import chain compounds these issues, so I should look at the eval-performance guidance to prioritize fixes.","outputTokens":670,"requestId":"1C00:1300AE:291B0D:30C498:69E82116"},"id":"5943b1bc-4c75-4674-be61-fe9ee84540d7","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:15:21.375Z","parentId":"dcb53fae-81c9-4374-a9da-b5440db27ae1"}
